Here's how to handle draft persistence with .NET MAUI's app lifecycle events:

**In your `App.xaml.cs`**, hook into the lifecycle:

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    public App()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        MainPage = new NavigationPage(new NotePage());
    }

    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState activationState)
    {
        var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);

        window.Deactivated += (s, e) =>
        {
            // Save draft when app goes to background
            if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage is NotePage page)
                page.SaveDraft();
        };

        window.Activated += (s, e) =>
        {
            // Restore draft when app comes back
            if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage is NotePage page)
                page.RestoreDraft();
        };

        return window;
    }
}
```

**In your `NotePage.xaml.cs`**:

```csharp
public partial class NotePage : ContentPage
{
    private const string DraftKey = "note_draft";

    public NotePage()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        RestoreDraft();
    }

    public void SaveDraft()
    {
        Preferences.Set(DraftKey, NoteEditor.Text ?? string.Empty);
    }

    public void RestoreDraft()
    {
        if (Preferences.ContainsKey(DraftKey))
            NoteEditor.Text = Preferences.Get(DraftKey, string.Empty);
    }

    // Call this when the user explicitly saves/discards
    public void ClearDraft()
    {
        Preferences.Remove(DraftKey);
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`Preferences`** is ideal for small text — it's synchronous, fast, and persists across app restarts.
- **`Window.Deactivated`** fires when the app loses focus (backgrounded or switched away).
- **`Window.Activated`** fires when the app regains focus.
- For large drafts (>1MB), use `FileSystem.AppDataDirectory` with file I/O instead of `Preferences`.
- Call `ClearDraft()` when the user intentionally saves or discards the note.
